{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[PASS 1 — G6 Approach soundness, anti-patterns & alternative-selection]\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (criteria this plan satisfies):\n- G6 FITNESS-FOR-PURPOSE: the solution targets the named problem directly — a moving shared checkout producing a false-negative verdict — by reading a snapshot pinned to an immutable SHA rather than a proxy. Not a proxy fix.\n- G6 MECHANISM CORRECTNESS (signing channel): the \"bind verified_at_sha via the EXISTING manifest channel, not a payload field\" decision is verified-correct against the code: signing.py:188-201 `_canonical_payload` signs `{v, algorithm, ticket_id, manifest}` and signs the full `manifest: list[str]` (compute_signature, signing.py:204-206); a `verified-at-sha:<sha>` manifest step therefore enters the signed bytes WITHOUT touching `_canonical_payload` or bumping `PAYLOAD_VERSION`, so prior signatures still verify exactly as the plan claims. Mechanism sound.\n- G6 MECHANISM CORRECTNESS (concurrency / TOCTOU): the content-addressed (immutable-SHA-keyed) cache + single-flight + POSIX delete-on-last-close reader model avoids the classic check-then-act race, and the pin write is serialized through the existing optimistic-concurrency/compare-and-set boundary (S4 30b3) — the atomicity mechanism is NAMED, not merely asserted. read-tree+checkout-index over `git archive` is correctly justified (archive drops export-ignore/LFS/export-subst). Edge/concurrent/failure cases (fetch-auth fail-closed, ENOENT→re-materialize, crashed-materialization tmp/ sweep) are handled.\n- G6 APPROACH SELECTION: I generated and weighed structurally-different alternatives — (a) per-ref `git worktree` checkouts instead of content-addressed materialized snapshots, (b) `git archive` tarball materialization, (c) a new signed-payload SHA field instead of the manifest channel. Each is inferior on the dimensions that matter here (worktrees take index/HEAD locks and contend under concurrency; archive is lossy/unfaithful for an attestation; a payload field invalidates every prior signature). The chosen approach is defensibly at-least-as-good on codebase-alignment, blast-radius, and robustness. No clearly-superior missed alternative — PASS, alternatives discarded.\n- G6 POSITIVE RATIONALE: present and explicit (de-risking order \"riskiest piece first\"; why manifest-channel over payload-schema; why read-tree over archive; design grounded against Gitaly/Sourcegraph/Bazel/Nix/in-toto). PASS.\n\nFINDING (G6 — MECHANISM CORRECTNESS: the chosen approach's data-flow is incomplete for the plan-review gate; its verdict-producing hash path still reads the mutable checkout, so the plan does not fully achieve its own AC1/AC2 for that gate as decomposed):\n- criteria: G6 (mechanism actually achieves the goal — data-flow complete, no path left reading the wrong source).\n- location: parent AC1 (\"No code-reading gate reads the server's working tree in attested mode\") + AC2 (reproducible); \"What\" bullet \"point the gate's file tools (pai_tools root / cfg.repo_path) at the snapshot dir\" (S3 fa49 What/Scope/file_impact); S4b e308 file_impact; src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py:106, :195, :325.\n- evidence:\n  1. The plan re-roots only the LLM *file tools* onto the snapshot (S3 fa49: \"point the gate's file tools (pai_tools root / cfg.repo_path) at the snapshot dir\"; file_impact = completion.py / pai_tools.py / mcp_server.py).\n  2. But the plan-review gate's verdict/attestation hashing is computed elsewhere, all rooted on the MUTABLE checkout via `_config.repo_root`: `dependency_hashes()` (attest.py:106-107) signs the file_impact map from the working tree; `_rehash()` (attest.py:191-196, \"Re-hash … at CURRENT working-tree content\"); the ADR-0002 claim-gate freshness re-check (attest.py:325-326). None reads a snapshot dir.\n  3. The plan DID create a dedicated child for this coherence — S4b `piney-gold-day` (e308) — but its file_impact is `src/rebar/signing.py` + the ADR doc, NOT `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py` where the three hash sites actually live. So no child re-roots attest.py onto the pinned-SHA snapshot.\n  4. Consequence (mechanism gap, not just ownership): an attested plan-review signs file_impact hashes, but the later claim-gate freshness re-check re-hashes the same paths from the server working tree (possibly a different branch / dirty) → spurious \"stale-code\" drift, OR a re-hash that silently passes against the WRONG branch — re-introducing exactly the moving-checkout false-verdict this epic exists to eliminate. The plan's stated mechanism (\"never the server's mutable checkout\") is therefore not achieved for the plan-review gate's hashing path.\n- checklist_item: - [ ] Close the plan-review hashing data-flow: make `attest.py`'s `dependency_hashes()` (:106), `_rehash()` (:195), and the ADR-0002 freshness re-check (:325) hash from the pinned-SHA snapshot basis rather than `_config.repo_root`, so the plan-review gate's verdict/attestation path actually reads the snapshot (AC1/AC2) — and name `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py` in the file_impact of whichever child owns it (S3 fa49 or S4b e308), since today no child lists it.\n- suggested_fix: Add `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/attest.py` to S4b (e308) file_impact and extend its shared-ref-resolution boundary to route the pinned-SHA snapshot base into all three hash sites (dependency_hashes / _rehash / freshness re-check) in place of `_config.repo_root`; alternatively fold those three sites into S3's re-rooting scope. Either way, exactly one child must name attest.py so the snapshot basis reaches the hashing path the signed verdict depends on.\n"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782531252845727001,"uuid":"62544407-a6ef-4603-ac39-ec2343d842a1"}